    "A trivial adversarial strategy is to guess at random, giving a success probability of 1/2 and, for a secure protocol, we ask that a computationally unbounded adversary cannot distinguish the bit strings with success probability greater than 1 2 +p dist, for p dist ≪ 1.",
    "In other words, the best strategy, even for a very powerful adversary, is not much better than the trivial one.",
    "This definition of security is formalised using distance measures as follows.Definition 2 (Statistical distance).",
    "The statistical distance ∆ between two random variables X and Y, with X, Y ∈ {0, 1} n, conditioned on information E (a random variable of arbitrary dimension), is given by∆(X, Y |E) = 1 2 x,e |p X|E=e (x) -p Y |E=e (x)|.",
    "(2)If X and Y satisfy ∆(X, Y |E) ≤ ϵ, we say that they are ϵ-close (given E), which implies that they can be distinguished with advantage p dist ≤ ϵ 2."
